      Block trades
   =20
 =20

Here=E2=80=99s a simple model of a block trade. There=E2=80=99s a public co=
mpany, its stock trades on the exchange, its current price is $100. A big s=
hareholder wants to sell a block of a million shares. This will drive down =
the price: supply and demand, more sellers than buyers, etc. Let=E2=80=99s =
say that fully selling all of the shares will drive the price down by $3.
You=E2=80=99re a bank, and the seller comes to you and says: =E2=80=9CI wan=
t to do a block trade. I want you to buy all this stock at a firm price and=
 resell it at your own risk. You have to buy it after the market closes in =
two hours; I=E2=80=99ll call you for your bid then.=E2=80=9D How much shoul=
d you bid? Well, on my numbers in the previous paragraph, the stock is at $=
100, selling all the shares will take $3 off the price, and you=E2=80=99ll =
be able to resell it at $97. So you should bid, like, $96, to add a little =
cushion (in case that $3 estimate of the price impact is wrong)=C2=A0and so=
me profit for you.
But in fact the stock will move around over the next two hours. Maybe in tw=
o hours it=E2=80=99ll be $99, or $101. And=C2=A0reselling the stock will dr=
ive it down by $3. So really your bid should be (1) whatever the closing pr=
ice is in two hours minus (2) say,=C2=A0$4 (the $3 effect of the sale, plus=
 $1 for your profits). And in fact the seller will probably ask you for a b=
id that is not a dollar price but a discount (percentage or dollars) to the=
 last sale price. If the stock closes at $99.73 and your bid is =E2=80=9Cdo=
wn $4=E2=80=9D then your bid is $95.73.
You have two hours to come up with your bid. You have two goals:
=09
Accuracy:=C2=A0You want your bid to accurately reflect the price at which y=
ou can resell the stock (plus a little profit for you); you don=E2=80=99t w=
ant to pay $98 if you=E2=80=99ll have to resell the stock at $95.=09
Competitiveness: The seller is probably calling a bunch of banks, and will =
take the highest price (the lowest discount to the last sale). So you want =
to offer the highest price.

Here is a good trick: You spend those two hours=C2=A0selling all the stock.=
 You pre-sell the million shares that the seller is offering; you sell them=
 short.=C2=A0As you do this, naturally, the price declines, from $100 to $9=
7, to reflect all of that selling. (Also maybe other stuff happens =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0maybe there=E2=80=99s economic news or other big buyers or sellers=
 or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0so the stock ends up at $96 or $98 or whatever,=
 but the $3 effect of all the selling is fully incorporated into the price.=
) And then at the end of that process you go to the seller and bid =E2=80=
=9Cdown $1=E2=80=9D: That is, you=E2=80=99ll pay $1 less than the last pric=
e; if the last price was $97 you=E2=80=99ll pay $96.
Now, two things are true:
=09Your bid is more accurate. You already know the price you can get for al=
l that stock, because you=E2=80=99ve already sold it. If you sold it at $97=
 and bid $96, you have $1 of profit that is totally safe.
  [1]

=09Your bid is=C2=A0tighter, more competitive. Instead of bidding =E2=80=9C=
down $4,=E2=80=9D as you would have in the naive case, you bid =E2=80=9Cdow=
n $1,=E2=80=9D because the $3 impact of selling the stock is already reflec=
ted=C2=A0into the price.

Notice that your bid is not=C2=A0actually better:=C2=A0In the naive case, t=
he stock is at $100 and you bid down $4 ($96) to reflect the likely impact =
on the price of reselling all the stock. In the pre-selling case, the stock=
 is at $97 and you bid down $1 ($96) because you=E2=80=99ve already resold =
all the stock. Either way the seller gets $96.
But if you are in competition, your competitors don=E2=80=99t know that you=
=E2=80=99ve pre-sold the stock. They see the closing price of $97 and think=
 that that reflects the market=E2=80=99s valuation of the stock; they think=
 that reselling the million-share block will require=C2=A0another=C2=A0$3 p=
rice drop. So they bid =E2=80=9Cdown $4=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0the naive b=
id =E2=80=94=C2=A0which works out to $93. And you bid $96, you win, you get=
 the stock, and you make an easy $1 profit.
There are some problems with this trick. One is, if you do it and=C2=A0don=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0win, you=E2=80=99ve pre-sold all this stock and don=E2=80=
=99t get to buy it at a discount; you have to go and cover your short in th=
e market and might lose money. What if another bank does the same trick? Th=
en, between you, you=E2=80=99ve sold two=C2=A0million shares, the price has=
 gone down=C2=A0too=C2=A0far, and whoever loses the auction will have to bu=
y back the million shares at higher prices. What if five banks do this tric=
k?
There are ways to mitigate this risk. A simple one is, instead of actually=
=C2=A0pre-selling the stock yourself, you just call up the likely buyers =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the big hedge funds that tend to buy block trades =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and say =E2=80=9Chey, got one coming for Amalgamated Widgets, you in?=
=E2=80=9D And then the hedge funds give you an order, and they short the st=
ock, and it goes down to $97, and you proceed as above,=C2=A0bidding $96 an=
d winning the auction, and you sell=C2=A0them the stock at $96.50 and they =
make money and you make money. This moves the risk from=C2=A0you to the hed=
ge funds.
  [2]

Another problem with this trick is that it is pretty bad customer service.=
=C2=A0It=C2=A0looks=C2=A0like good customer=C2=A0service: You can give the =
seller a tight bid on the block, and then resell it quickly and efficiently=
. But it is=C2=A0actually=C2=A0bad customer service, because you drive down=
 the price ahead of the block trade and make the auction for the seller=E2=
=80=99s shares less competitive.
  [3]
 Ordinarily sellers will swear you to secrecy; they will call you up and sa=
y =E2=80=9CI want you to bid on this block, but don=E2=80=99t tell anyone t=
hat it=E2=80=99s coming.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0If the seller finds out that you did=
 pre-sell the shares, or that you leaked the news to hedge funds to pre-sel=
l the shares, they will be mad at you.
  [4]

A third problem with this trick is that it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I was about to=
 say =E2=80=9Cvery illegal,=E2=80=9D but apparently it is only, like, the r=
egular amount of illegal. Possibly less. It is mildly illegal? (Not=C2=A0le=
gal advice!) It is a form of=C2=A0insider trading, or rather front-running:=
=C2=A0Your client (the big shareholder) called you and said =E2=80=9CI want=
 to sell stock after the close today,=E2=80=9D and probably swore you to se=
crecy, and then you went and traded on it, or told hedge funds to trade on =
it, so you could make more money for yourself with less risk. You had=C2=A0=
nonpublic information about a big shareholder=E2=80=99s plans to sell, that=
 information was material, you had a duty to keep it confidential, and inst=
ead you used it to tip off some hedge funds (or trade yourself) to make mon=
ey for yourself.
A certain amount of illegal. On Friday, the  US Securities and Exchange Com=
mission=C2=A0and  US federal prosecutors in Manhattan=C2=A0settled a case=
=C2=A0against Morgan Stanley and Pawan Passi, its former head of US equity =
syndicate. =E2=80=9CEquity syndicate=E2=80=9D is the desk that does this st=
uff; specifically:
=09When big shareholders ask for a price on a block trade, equity syndicate=
 is the desk that gives them the price.=09When Morgan Stanley wins a block =
trade, equity syndicate is the desk that coordinates selling the shares out=
 to investors.=09When big shareholders ask for a price on a block trade, eq=
uity syndicate is=C2=A0the desk that calls potential investors and say =E2=
=80=9Chey what price would you pay for this block?=E2=80=9D to formulate it=
s bid.


Oh, I mean, not really;=C2=A0No. 3 is illegal. But kind of. Certainly Pawan=
 Passi did that, though now he is the former head of equity syndicate.  The=
 SEC says:

Selling shareholders or their agents then typically send a bid-wanted-in-co=
mpetition (=E2=80=9CBWIC=E2=80=9D) email to the investment banking firms th=
at had expressed an interest on the initial outreach calls. BWICs are typic=
ally sent to firms two to three hours before the market close. They reitera=
te the information provided on the outreach call (the seller=E2=80=99s iden=
tity, the stock, and size of the block), request bids by 4:05 pm ET that da=
y, and set forth the confidential auction process. BWICs typically pre-cond=
ition a firm=E2=80=99s participation in the auction process on the firm agr=
eeing to keep information about the potential block trade confidential. Sel=
ling shareholders or their agents require the select group of auction parti=
cipants to keep such information confidential because if the market becomes=
 aware of an imminent block trade, as stated above, the price of the stock =
might decline, and the seller might receive a worse price from the auction.=
 =E2=80=A6
During the Relevant Period, Passi disclosed non-public, potentially market-=
moving information received from selling shareholders or their agents about=
 block trades to certain potential purchasers of the block, including a por=
tfolio manager (=E2=80=9CPortfolio Manager A=E2=80=9D) in the London, Engla=
nd office of a Hong-Kong-based hedge fund (=E2=80=9CHedge Fund A=E2=80=9D) =
while the auction process was ongoing. ...
Passi provided this information to Portfolio Manager A with the understandi=
ng that he would take large short positions in the stock in anticipation, a=
nd prior to the execution, of the block trade, and that, if Morgan Stanley =
won the auction, Portfolio Manager A would request and receive allocations =
from the block trade to cover those short positions.=C2=A0
Passi knew that providing information about block trades to buy-side invest=
ors, such as Portfolio Manager A, could cause the stock price to decline if=
 those investors sold significant amounts of stock in advance of the block =
trade.
Portfolio Manager A=E2=80=99s pre-positioning activities benefitted Morgan =
Stanley as they ensured that there would be a large buyer for at least a po=
rtion of the block trade, thereby lowering Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s risk on=
 the transaction, and giving the firm comfort to offer a tighter and more c=
ompetitive bid.

It seems that Passi called=C2=A0several investors to place a bunch of the s=
tock (and thus largely de-risk Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s bid), but it=E2=80=
=99s not clear how methodical he was; it=E2=80=99s possible that he just ca=
lled a few of his favorites. For instance this guy, from the  criminal stat=
ement of facts:
Hedge fund investors who received confidential information from the Head of=
 the Desk [Passi] and Employee-1 about upcoming blocks recognized that this=
 information allowed them to profit in ways they otherwise would not have. =
For example, an investor working at a Nevada- based hedge fund (=E2=80=9CIn=
vestor-3=E2=80=9D) told the Head of the Desk in an August 2021 call, =E2=80=
=9CI know who my daddy is,=E2=80=9D referring to the assistance that the He=
ad of the Desk had provided Investor-3 in profiting from block trades. Inve=
stor-3 stated in the same call, again referring to block trades, that the H=
ead of the Desk had =E2=80=9Cput [Investor-3] in the ... game,=E2=80=9D and=
 that Investor-3 =E2=80=9Cwould be at the kiddie table if it wasn=E2=80=99t=
 for=E2=80=9D the Head of the Desk.
Because, yes, if you do this right, it is nearly risk-free profit for the h=
edge fund (who shorts the stock during the day and then gets it back at the=
 close at a discount to the trading price) and for Morgan Stanley (who lock=
s in buyers a higher price than it agrees to pay the seller). You don=E2=80=
=99t need to be a big or good hedge fund to get the call for this trade; yo=
u just need to be a loyal friend of Passi=E2=80=99s.
Anyway, two related points. One is that this is=C2=A0illegal, but it=E2=80=
=99s on a continuum. As a general matter, when you want to sell a large blo=
ck of stock, you have to balance your desires to (1) tell everyone, to drum=
 up buyers and (2)=C2=A0tell no one, to avoid anyone front-running you. In =
different circumstances, you might strike that balance in different ways. S=
ometimes, it is=C2=A0good=C2=A0customer service for Morgan Stanley to =E2=
=80=9Csocialize=E2=80=9D a block trade before bidding, to pre-market it bef=
ore actually doing the trade. Ordinarily to do that you=E2=80=99d wall-cros=
s the investors first: You=E2=80=99d call them up to ask =E2=80=9Chey would=
 you buy this block,=E2=80=9D but only if they first promise not to short t=
he stock ahead of the trade.=C2=A0In fact Morgan Stanley marketed that serv=
ice; from the statement of facts:
When Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s marketing materials referenced investor outre=
ach, the materials suggested that such outreach would be done only to inves=
tors that had been wall-crossed. Sellers were told that while block trades =
were one option for selling their shares, another option was an =E2=80=9Cov=
ernight with wall-cross and backstop,=E2=80=9D which was described as a reg=
istered sale that would =E2=80=9Claunch[] publicly after wall-crossing seve=
ral investors capable of acting as anchor investors.=E2=80=9D The stated ad=
vantage of this =E2=80=9Covernight with a wall-cross=E2=80=9D was that =E2=
=80=9Canchor investor feedback helps provide early pricing insight ahead of=
 public launch.=E2=80=9D In other slides shown to potential sellers, the po=
ssibility of wall-crossing a select number of investors =E2=80=9Cahead of l=
aunch to maximize demand visibility/pricing=E2=80=9D was offered as a possi=
ble way to execute a registered block trade.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s just that, when sellers instead chose to do block trades witho=
ut pre-marketing, Passi pre-marketed the shares anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0not t=
o benefit the client but to benefit Morgan Stanley. (Also Passi =E2=80=9Cdi=
d not wall cross any investors before sharing confidential information abou=
t the Relevant Blocks with them.=E2=80=9D)
Even without wall-crossing, though, there are some gray areas about what so=
rt of information-gathering a syndicate desk can do before putting in a bid=
. Like:
=09Calling up some hedge funds at 2 p.m. and saying =E2=80=9Chey we got a b=
lock of Amalgamated Widgets coming after the close today, are you in? If so=
 you should=C2=A0short the stock now=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0pretty illegal.=09Calli=
ng up some hedge funds at 2 p.m. and saying =E2=80=9Cjust hypothetically, h=
ow are you feeling about the widget sector these days,=E2=80=9D to get a se=
nse of investor demand: maybe okay?

You can get some deniability on these calls. Though some sellers know to lo=
ok out for this; the SEC notes that one selling shareholder=E2=80=99s agent=
 sent Morgan Stanley a bid-wanted-in-competition request that said:
Prior to the purchaser being selected, please do not engage in any discussi=
on with potential investors or purchasers, even hypothetical ones, includin=
g discussions in which several names are mentioned in order to solicit gene=
ral interest.
The other point is that this is illegal, but apparently not that illegal. M=
organ Stanley paid a total of $249 million of penalties to the SEC and $153=
