<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a simple model of a block trade=
. There=E2=80=99s a public company, its stock trades on the exchange, its c=
urrent price is $100. A big shareholder wants to sell a block of a million =
shares. This will drive down the price: supply and demand, more sellers tha=
n buyers, etc. Let=E2=80=99s say that fully selling all of the shares will =
drive the price down by $3.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You=E2=80=99re a bank, and the seller comes to=
 you and says: =E2=80=9CI want to do a block trade. I want you to buy all t=
his stock at a firm price and resell it at your own risk. You have to buy i=
t after the market closes in two hours; I=E2=80=99ll call you for your bid =
then.=E2=80=9D How much should you bid? Well, on my numbers in the previous=
 paragraph, the stock is at $100, selling all the shares will take $3 off t=
he price, and you=E2=80=99ll be able to resell it at $97. So you should bid=
, like, $96, to add a little cushion (in case that $3 estimate of the price=
 impact is wrong)=C2=A0and some profit for you.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in fact the stock will move around over th=
e next two hours. Maybe in two hours it=E2=80=99ll be $99, or $101. And=C2=
=A0reselling the stock will drive it down by $3. So really your bid should =
be (1) whatever the closing price is in two hours minus (2) say,=C2=A0$4 (t=
he $3 effect of the sale, plus $1 for your profits). And in fact the seller=
 will probably ask you for a bid that is not a dollar price but a discount =
(percentage or dollars) to the last sale price. If the stock closes at $99.=
73 and your bid is =E2=80=9Cdown $4=E2=80=9D then your bid is $95.73.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You have two hours to come up with your bid. Y=
ou have two goals:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Accuracy:=C2=A0</em>You want your bid to accurately reflect the price a=
t which you can resell the stock (plus a little profit for you); you don=E2=
=80=99t want to pay $98 if you=E2=80=99ll have to resell the stock at $95.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Competitiveness:</em> The seller is probably calling a bunch of banks, =
and will take the highest price (the lowest discount to the last sale). So =
you want to offer the highest price.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a good trick: You spend those two hour=
s=C2=A0<em>selling all the stock</em>. You pre-sell the million shares that=
 the seller is offering; you sell them short.=C2=A0As you do this, naturall=
y, the price declines, from $100 to $97, to reflect all of that selling. (A=
lso maybe other stuff happens =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe there=E2=80=99s economic=
 news or other big buyers or sellers or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0so the stoc=
k ends up at $96 or $98 or whatever, but the $3 effect of all the selling i=
s fully incorporated into the price.) And then at the end of that process y=
ou go to the seller and bid =E2=80=9Cdown $1=E2=80=9D: That is, you=E2=80=
=99ll pay $1 less than the last price; if the last price was $97 you=E2=80=
=99ll pay $96.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, two things are true:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your bid is more accurate. You alread=
y know the price you can get for all that stock, because you=E2=80=99ve alr=
eady sold it. If you sold it at $97 and bid $96, you have $1 of profit that=
 is totally safe.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your bid is=C2=A0<em>tighter</em>=
, more competitive. Instead of bidding =E2=80=9Cdown $4,=E2=80=9D as you wo=
uld have in the naive case, you bid =E2=80=9Cdown $1,=E2=80=9D because the =
$3 impact of selling the stock is already reflected=C2=A0into the price.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice that your bid is not=C2=A0<em>actually =
better:=C2=A0</em>In the naive case, the stock is at $100 and you bid down =
$4 ($96) to reflect the likely impact on the price of reselling all the sto=
ck. In the pre-selling case, the stock is at $97 and you bid down $1 ($96) =
because you=E2=80=99ve already resold all the stock. Either way the seller =
gets $96.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you are in competition, your competitor=
s don=E2=80=99t know that you=E2=80=99ve pre-sold the stock. They see the c=
losing price of $97 and think that that reflects the market=E2=80=99s valua=
tion of the stock; they think that reselling the million-share block will r=
equire=C2=A0<em>another=C2=A0</em>$3 price drop. So they bid =E2=80=9Cdown =
$4=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0the naive bid =E2=80=94=C2=A0which works out to =
$93. And you bid $96, you win, you get the stock, and you make an easy $1 p=
rofit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are some problems with this trick. One i=
s, if you do it and=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>win, you=E2=80=99ve pr=
e-sold all this stock and don=E2=80=99t get to buy it at a discount; you ha=
ve to go and cover your short in the market and might lose money. What if a=
nother bank does the same trick? Then, between you, you=E2=80=99ve sold <em=
>two=C2=A0</em>million shares, the price has gone down=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</=
em>far, and whoever loses the auction will have to buy back the million sha=
res at higher prices. What if five banks do this trick?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are ways to mitigate this risk. A simple=
 one is, instead of actually<em>=C2=A0</em>pre-selling the stock yourself, =
you just call up the likely buyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0the big hedge funds that =
tend to buy block trades =E2=80=94=C2=A0and say =E2=80=9Chey, got one comin=
g for Amalgamated Widgets, you in?=E2=80=9D And then the hedge funds give y=
ou an order, and <em>they </em>short the stock, and it goes down to $97, an=
d you proceed as above,=C2=A0bidding $96 and winning the auction, and you s=
ell=C2=A0them the stock at $96.50 and they make money and you make money. T=
his moves the risk from=C2=A0you to the hedge funds.<a class=3D"footnote-in=
dex" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; disp=
lay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another problem with this trick is that it is =
pretty bad customer service.=C2=A0It=C2=A0<em>looks=C2=A0</em>like good cus=
tomer=C2=A0service: You can give the seller a tight bid on the block, and t=
hen resell it quickly and efficiently. But it is=C2=A0<em>actually=C2=A0</e=
m>bad customer service, because you drive down the price ahead of the block=
 trade and make the auction for the seller=E2=80=99s shares less competitiv=
e.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tra=
nsparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> Ordinarily sellers will swear you to secrecy; they will call you up an=
d say =E2=80=9CI want you to bid on this block, but don=E2=80=99t tell anyo=
ne that it=E2=80=99s coming.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0If the seller finds out that you=
 did pre-sell the shares, or that you leaked the news to hedge funds to pre=
-sell the shares, they will be mad at you.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third problem with this trick is that it is =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0I was about to say =E2=80=9Cvery illegal,=E2=80=9D but appar=
ently it is only, like, the regular amount of illegal. Possibly less. It is=
 mildly illegal? (Not=C2=A0legal advice!) It is a form of=C2=A0<em>insider =
trading</em>, or rather front-running:=C2=A0Your client (the big shareholde=
r) called you and said =E2=80=9CI want to sell stock after the close today,=
=E2=80=9D and probably swore you to secrecy, and then you went and traded o=
n it, or told hedge funds to trade on it, so you could make more money for =
yourself with less risk. You had=C2=A0nonpublic information about a big sha=
reholder=E2=80=99s plans to sell, that information was material, you had a =
duty to keep it confidential, and instead you used it to tip off some hedge=
 funds (or trade yourself) to make money for yourself.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A certain amount of illegal. On Friday, the <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34017514.287406/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyNC02/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB41103980" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> US Securities and Exchange Commission</a>=C2=A0an=
d <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34017514.287406/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1zZG55L3ByL3VzLWF0dG9ybmV5LWFubm91bmN=
lcy1hZ3JlZW1lbnRzLW1vcmdhbi1zdGFubGV5LWFuZC1mb3JtZXItc2VuaW9yLWVtcGxveWVlLX=
Bhd2FuLXBhc3Np/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBedce6002" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> US federal prose=
cutors in Manhattan</a>=C2=A0settled a case=C2=A0against Morgan Stanley and=
 Pawan Passi, its former head of US equity syndicate. =E2=80=9CEquity syndi=
cate=E2=80=9D is the desk that does this stuff; specifically:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When big shareholders ask for a price=
 on a block trade, equity syndicate is the desk that gives them the price.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When Morgan Stanley wins a block t=
rade, equity syndicate is the desk that coordinates selling the shares out =
to investors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When big shareholder=
s ask for a price on a block trade, equity syndicate is=C2=A0<em>the desk t=
hat calls potential investors and say =E2=80=9Chey what price would you pay=
 for this block?=E2=80=9D to formulate its bid.</em>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, I mean, not really;=C2=A0No. 3 is illegal.=
 But kind of. Certainly Pawan Passi did that, though now he is the <em>form=
er</em> head of equity syndicate. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/34017514.287406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F=
0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjQvMzQtOTkzMzcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5fafaaa5" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> The SEC says</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Selling shareholders or their agents then typi=
cally send a bid-wanted-in-competition (=E2=80=9CBWIC=E2=80=9D) email to th=
e investment banking firms that had expressed an interest on the initial ou=
treach calls. BWICs are typically sent to firms two to three hours before t=
he market close. They reiterate the information provided on the outreach ca=
ll (the seller=E2=80=99s identity, the stock, and size of the block), reque=
st bids by 4:05 pm ET that day, and set forth the confidential auction proc=
ess. BWICs typically pre-condition a firm=E2=80=99s participation in the au=
ction process on the firm agreeing to keep information about the potential =
block trade confidential. Selling shareholders or their agents require the =
select group of auction participants to keep such information confidential =
because if the market becomes aware of an imminent block trade, as stated a=
bove, the price of the stock might decline, and the seller might receive a =
worse price from the auction. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the Relevant Period, Passi disclosed no=
n-public, potentially market-moving information received from selling share=
holders or their agents about block trades to certain potential purchasers =
of the block, including a portfolio manager (=E2=80=9CPortfolio Manager A=
=E2=80=9D) in the London, England office of a Hong-Kong-based hedge fund (=
=E2=80=9CHedge Fund A=E2=80=9D) while the auction process was ongoing. ...<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Passi provided this information to Portfolio M=
anager A with the understanding that he would take large short positions in=
 the stock in anticipation, and prior to the execution, of the block trade,=
 and that, if Morgan Stanley won the auction, Portfolio Manager A would req=
uest and receive allocations from the block trade to cover those short posi=
tions.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Passi knew that providing information about bl=
ock trades to buy-side investors, such as Portfolio Manager A, could cause =
the stock price to decline if those investors sold significant amounts of s=
tock in advance of the block trade.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Portfolio Manager A=E2=80=99s pre-positioning =
activities benefitted Morgan Stanley as they ensured that there would be a =
large buyer for at least a portion of the block trade, thereby lowering Mor=
gan Stanley=E2=80=99s risk on the transaction, and giving the firm comfort =
to offer a tighter and more competitive bid.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It seems that Passi called=C2=A0several invest=
ors to place a bunch of the stock (and thus largely de-risk Morgan Stanley=
=E2=80=99s bid), but it=E2=80=99s not clear how methodical he was; it=E2=80=
=99s possible that he just called a few of his favorites. For instance this=
 guy, from the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/340=
17514.287406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvbWVkaWEvMTMzMzIwNi9kbA/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB904ed903" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> criminal statement of facts</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hedge fund investors who received =
confidential information from the Head of the Desk [Passi] and Employee-1 a=
bout upcoming blocks recognized that this information allowed them to profi=
t in ways they otherwise would not have. For example, an investor working a=
t a Nevada- based hedge fund (=E2=80=9CInvestor-3=E2=80=9D) told the Head o=
f the Desk in an August 2021 call, =E2=80=9CI know who my daddy is,=E2=80=
=9D referring to the assistance that the Head of the Desk had provided Inve=
stor-3 in profiting from block trades. Investor-3 stated in the same call, =
again referring to block trades, that the Head of the Desk had =E2=80=9Cput=
 [Investor-3] in the ... game,=E2=80=9D and that Investor-3 =E2=80=9Cwould =
be at the kiddie table if it wasn=E2=80=99t for=E2=80=9D the Head of the De=
sk.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because, yes, if you do this right, it is near=
ly risk-free profit for the hedge fund (who shorts the stock during the day=
 and then gets it back at the close at a discount to the trading price) and=
 for Morgan Stanley (who locks in buyers a higher price than it agrees to p=
ay the seller). You don=E2=80=99t need to be a big or good hedge fund to ge=
t the call for this trade; you just need to be a loyal friend of Passi=E2=
=80=99s.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, two related points. One is that this i=
s=C2=A0<em>illegal</em>, but it=E2=80=99s on a continuum. As a general matt=
er, when you want to sell a large block of stock, you have to balance your =
desires to (1) tell everyone, to drum up buyers and (2)=C2=A0tell no one, t=
o avoid anyone front-running you. In different circumstances, you might str=
ike that balance in different ways. <em>Sometimes</em>, it is=C2=A0<em>good=
=C2=A0</em>customer service for Morgan Stanley to =E2=80=9Csocialize=E2=80=
=9D a block trade before bidding, to pre-market it before actually doing th=
e trade. Ordinarily to do that you=E2=80=99d wall-cross the investors first=
: You=E2=80=99d call them up to ask =E2=80=9Chey would you buy this block,=
=E2=80=9D but only if they first promise not to short the stock ahead of th=
e trade.=C2=A0In fact Morgan Stanley marketed that service; from the statem=
ent of facts:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Morgan Stanley=E2=80=99s mark=
eting materials referenced investor outreach, the materials suggested that =
such outreach would be done only to investors that had been wall-crossed. S=
ellers were told that while block trades were one option for selling their =
shares, another option was an =E2=80=9Covernight with wall-cross and backst=
op,=E2=80=9D which was described as a registered sale that would =E2=80=9Cl=
aunch[] publicly after wall-crossing several investors capable of acting as=
 anchor investors.=E2=80=9D The stated advantage of this =E2=80=9Covernight=
 with a wall-cross=E2=80=9D was that =E2=80=9Canchor investor feedback help=
s provide early pricing insight ahead of public launch.=E2=80=9D In other s=
lides shown to potential sellers, the possibility of wall-crossing a select=
 number of investors =E2=80=9Cahead of launch to maximize demand visibility=
/pricing=E2=80=9D was offered as a possible way to execute a registered blo=
ck trade.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s just that, when sellers instead c=
hose to do block trades without pre-marketing, Passi pre-marketed the share=
s anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0not to benefit the client but to benefit Morgan Sta=
nley. (Also Passi =E2=80=9Cdid not wall cross any investors before sharing =
confidential information about the Relevant Blocks with them.=E2=80=9D)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even without wall-crossing, though, there are =
some gray areas about what sort of information-gathering a syndicate desk c=
an do before putting in a bid. Like:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Calling up some hedge funds at 2 p.m. =
and saying =E2=80=9Chey we got a block of Amalgamated Widgets coming after =
the close today, are you in? If so you should=C2=A0short the stock now=E2=
=80=9D:=C2=A0pretty illegal.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Calli=
ng up some hedge funds at 2 p.m. and saying =E2=80=9Cjust hypothetically, h=
ow are you feeling about the widget sector these days,=E2=80=9D to get a se=
nse of investor demand: maybe okay?</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can get some deniability on these calls. T=
hough some sellers know to look out for this; the SEC notes that one sellin=
g shareholder=E2=80=99s agent sent Morgan Stanley a bid-wanted-in-competiti=
on request that said:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Prior to the purchaser being selec=
ted, please do not engage in any discussion with potential investors or pur=
chasers, even hypothetical ones, including discussions in which several nam=
es are mentioned in order to solicit general interest.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other point is that this is illegal, but a=
pparently not <em>that</em> illegal. Morgan Stanley paid a total of $249 mi=
llion of penalties to the SEC and $153 million to the Justice Department, t=
hough there is overlap in those numbers. (And some=C2=A0of the payment is f=
or restitution to the block sellers who got ripped off.) Meanwhile Passi wi=
ll pay $250,000 to the SEC and agreed to a deferred prosecution agreement i=
n the criminal case: He <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/34017514.287406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1zZG55L3ByL3VzL=
WF0dG9ybmV5LWFubm91bmNlcy1hZ3JlZW1lbnRzLW1vcmdhbi1zdGFubGV5LWFuZC1mb3JtZXIt=
c2VuaW9yLWVtcGxveWVlLXBhd2FuLXBhc3Np/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCedce6002" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> has to</a> =E2=80=9Cdemonstrate good behavior and fulfill the terms o=
f the DPA, in which case PASSI will not be further prosecuted criminally.=
=E2=80=9D So it=E2=80=99s not quite=C2=A0<em>real=C2=A0</em>insider trading=
: If you do this stuff they don=E2=80=99t send you to jail; you get a warni=
ng first.</p>
